  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/178451080?book_show_action=true">Jun 21, 2011</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="October " class="user" itemprop="url" name="October " href="/user/show/5668935-october">October </a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/9907608-the-time-machine-the-invisible-man">review of another edition</a>


        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5668935-october?shelf=science-fiction">science-fiction</a>, 
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/5668935-october?shelf=steampunk">steampunk</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer178451080" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer16851569694871711664">I wasn&apos;t expecting much from a time when fantasy and science fiction were not only in their infancy, but not acknowledged as being something for adults. However, having never read HG Wells in my entire life, I found him immensely entertainined. While the beginning of &quot;The Time Machine&quot; was a bit slow, I found the Darwinism (and the barely-hidden class commentary) of the future fascinating. However, I must say that I enjoyed &quot;The Invisible Man&quot; more than the time machine. Griffin is someone you c</span>
  <span id="freeText16851569694871711664" style="display:none">I wasn't expecting much from a time when fantasy and science fiction were not only in their infancy, but not acknowledged as being something for adults. However, having never read HG Wells in my entire life, I found him immensely entertainined. While the beginning of "The Time Machine" was a bit slow, I found the Darwinism (and the barely-hidden class commentary) of the future fascinating. However, I must say that I enjoyed "The Invisible Man" more than the time machine. Griffin is someone you can love to hate, and--according to some readers--may be a character alluding to terrorism. That in mind, I picked through "The Invisible Man" with a bit of interest; not because of the possible terrorism references, but because the Invisible Man was just...evil! After all, how do you protect yourself from something you can't see?<br /><br />Considering how tepid most science fiction has become in the age where Twilight and Harry Potter are considered the pinnacles of modern literature, looking back to the roots gives a reader something a bit more satisfying to read (and, of course, the lack of obvious self-insertion is much enjoyed).</span>
  <a data-text-id="16851569694871711664" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


